# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dhcp-snooping
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dhcp-snooping/dhcp-snooping] In computer networking, **DHCP snooping** is a series of techniques applied to improve the security of a Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) infrastructure.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dhcp-snooping] DHCP servers allocate IP addresses to clients on a LAN.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dhcp-snooping] DHCP snooping can be configured on LAN switches to exclude rogue DHCP servers and remove malicious or malformed DHCP traffic.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dhcp-snooping] In addition, information on hosts which have successfully completed a DHCP transaction is accrued in a database of *bindings* which may then be used by other security or accounting features.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dhcp-snooping] Other features may use DHCP snooping database information to ensure IP integrity on a Layer 2 switched domain.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-arp-inspection] The Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) has many security issues.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-arp-inspection] These include the Man In The Middle (MITM) attack through the ARP spoofing, ARP cache poisoning, Denial of Service and ARP poison routing attacks.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-arp-inspection] ArpON is a host-based solution that makes the ARP secure and avoids the man-in-the-middle attack through ARP spoofing, ARP cache poisoning or ARP poison routing.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-arp-inspection] The goal of ArpON is therefore to provide a secure and efficient network daemon that provides the SARPI, DARPI and HARPI anti-ARP-spoofing technique, thus making the ARP standardized protocol secure from any foreign intrusion.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The **Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol** (**DHCP**) is a network management protocol used on Internet Protocol (IP) networks for automatically assigning IP addresses and other communication parameters to devices connected to the network using a client–server architecture.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The technology eliminates the need for individually configuring network devices manually, and consists of two network components, a centrally installed network DHCP server and client instances of the protocol stack on each computer or device.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When connected to the network, and periodically thereafter, a client requests a set of parameters from the server using DHCP.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP can be implemented on networks ranging in size from residential networks to large campus networks and regional ISP networks.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Many routers and residential gateways have DHCP server capability.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Most residential network routers receive a unique IP address within the ISP network.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Within a local network, a DHCP server assigns a local IP address to each device.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP services exist for networks running Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4), as well as version 6 (IPv6).
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The IPv6 version of the DHCP protocol is commonly called DHCPv6.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The Reverse Address Resolution Protocol (RARP) was defined in 1984 for the configuration of simple devices, such as diskless workstations, with a suitable IP address.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Acting in the data link layer, it made implementation difficult on many server platforms.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] It required that a server be present on each individual network link.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] RARP was superseded by the Bootstrap Protocol (BOOTP) defined in September 1985.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This introduced the concept of a relay agent, which allowed the forwarding of BOOTP packets across networks, allowing one central BOOTP server to serve hosts on many IP subnets.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] It is based on BOOTP, but can dynamically allocate IP addresses from a pool and reclaim them when they are no longer in use.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] It can also be used to deliver a wide range of extra configuration parameters to IP clients, including platform-specific parameters.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Four years later, the DHCPINFORM message type (used for WPAD) and other small changes were added.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This definition, from 1997, remains the core of the standard for IPv4 networks.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] After updates by many subsequent RFCs, its definition was replaced in 2018, where prefix delegation and stateless address autoconfiguration were now merged.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Internet Protocol (IP) defines how devices communicate within and across local networks on the Internet.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP server can manage IP settings for devices on its local network, e.g., by assigning IP addresses to those devices automatically and dynamically.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP operates based on the client–server model.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When a computer or other device connects to a network, the DHCP client software sends a DHCP broadcast query requesting the necessary information.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Any DHCP server on the network may service the request.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP server manages a pool of IP addresses and information about client configuration parameters such as default gateway, domain name, the name servers, and time servers.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] On receiving a DHCP request, the DHCP server may respond with specific information for each client, as previously configured by an administrator, or with a specific address and any other information valid for the entire network and for the time period for which the allocation (*lease*) is valid.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP client typically queries this information immediately after booting, and periodically thereafter before the expiration of the information.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When a DHCP client refreshes an assignment, it initially requests the same parameter values, but the DHCP server may assign a new address based on the assignment policies set by administrators.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] On large networks that consist of multiple links, a single DHCP server may service the entire network when aided by DHCP relay agents located on the interconnecting routers.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Such agents relay messages between DHCP clients and DHCP servers located on different subnets.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The request-and-grant process uses a lease concept with a controllable time period, allowing the DHCP server to reclaim and then reallocate IP addresses that are not renewed.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP server permanently assigns an IP address to a requesting client from a range defined by an administrator.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This is like dynamic allocation, but the DHCP server keeps a table of past IP address assignments, so that it can preferentially assign to a client the same IP address that the client previously had.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] ) for each client to an IP address, which is offered to the requesting client.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP servers may be configured to fall back to other methods if this fails.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP services are used for Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) and IPv6.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The details of the protocol for IPv4 and IPv6 differ sufficiently that they may be considered separate protocols.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] For the IPv6 operation, devices may alternatively use stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] IPv6 hosts may also use link-local addressing to achieve operations restricted to the local network link.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP employs a connectionless service model, using the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] It is implemented with two UDP port numbers for its operations which are the same as for the bootstrap protocol (BOOTP).
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The server listens on UDP port number 67, and the client listens on UDP port number 68.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP operations fall into four phases: server discovery, IP lease offer, IP lease request, and IP lease acknowledgement.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] These stages are often abbreviated as DORA for discovery, offer, request, and acknowledgement.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP operation begins with clients broadcasting a request.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If the client and server are in different Broadcast Domains, a DHCP Helper or DHCP Relay Agent may be used.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Clients requesting renewal of an existing lease may communicate directly via UDP unicast, since the client already has an established IP address at that point.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Additionally, there is a BROADCAST flag (1 bit in 2 byte flags field, where all other bits are reserved and so are set to 0) the client can use to indicate in which way (broadcast or unicast) it can receive the DHCPOFFER: 0x8000 for broadcast, 0x0000 for unicast.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Usually, the DHCPOFFER is sent through unicast.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] For those hosts which cannot accept unicast packets before IP addresses are configured, this flag can be used to work around this issue.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP client broadcasts a DHCPDISCOVER message on the network subnet using the destination address *255.255.255.255* (limited broadcast) or the specific subnet broadcast address (directed broadcast).
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP client may also request an IP address in the DHCPDISCOVER, which the server may take into account when selecting an address to offer.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] For example, if HTYPE is set to 1, to specify that the medium used is Ethernet, HLEN is set to 6 because an Ethernet address (MAC address) is 6 octets long.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The CHADDR is set to the MAC address used by the client.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] IPv4 packet, containing a UDP PDU with DHCP payload...
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] 192 octets of 0s, or overflow space for additional options; BOOTP legacy.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When a DHCP server receives a DHCPDISCOVER message from a client, which is an IP address lease request, the DHCP server reserves an IP address for the client and makes a lease offer by sending a DHCPOFFER message to the client.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This message may contain the client's *Client ID* (Option 61, containing a unique value, traditionally a MAC address), the IP address that the server is offering, the subnet mask, the lease duration, and the IP address of the DHCP server making the offer.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP server may also take notice of the hardware-level MAC address (as specified in the CHADDR field).
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This field must be used to identify the client, if no Client ID is provided in the DHCP packet.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP server determines the configuration based on the client's hardware address as specified in the CHADDR (client hardware address) field.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In the following example the server (*192.168.1.1*) specifies the client's IP address in the YIADDR (your IP address) field.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In response to the DHCP offer, the client replies with a DHCPREQUEST message, broadcast to the server, requesting the offered address.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A client can receive DHCP offers from multiple servers, but it will accept only one DHCP offer.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The client must send the *server identification* option in the DHCPREQUEST message, indicating the server whose offer the client has selected.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When other DHCP servers receive this message, they withdraw any offers that they have made to the client and return their offered IP address to the pool of available addresses.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When the DHCP server receives the DHCPREQUEST message from the client, the configuration process enters its final phase.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The acknowledgement phase involves sending a DHCPACK packet to the client.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This packet includes the lease duration and any other configuration information that the client might have requested.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] At this point, the IP configuration process is completed.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The protocol expects the DHCP client to configure its network interface with the negotiated parameters.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When the server is reusing an IP address from its pool, it may first check (using ping) to see if it is not taken already.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This may happen if a host is configured manually with an IP address that lies within the DHCP scope.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Before claiming an IP address, the client should probe the newly received address (e.g. with ARP), in order to find if there is another host present in the network with the proposed IP address.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If there is no reply, this address does not conflict with that of another host, so it is free to be used.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If this probe finds another computer using that address, the client should broadcast a DHCPDECLINE to the DHCP server(s).
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP client may request more information than the server sent with the original DHCPOFFER.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The client may also request repeat data for a particular application.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] For example, browsers use *DHCP Inform* to obtain web proxy settings via WPAD.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The client sends a request to the DHCP server to release the DHCP information and the client deactivates its IP address.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] As client devices usually do not know when users may unplug them from the network, the protocol does not mandate the sending of *DHCP Release*.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP server can provide optional configuration parameters to the client.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] RFC 2132 describes the available DHCP options defined by Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) - DHCP and BOOTP PARAMETERS.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP client can select, manipulate and overwrite parameters provided by a DHCP server.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In Unix-like systems this client-level refinement typically takes place according to the values in the configuration file */etc/dhclient.conf*.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Options are octet strings of varying length.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This is called Type–length–value encoding.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The first octet is the option code, the second octet is the number of following octets and the remaining octets are code dependent.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] For example, the DHCP message-type option for an offer would appear as 0x35, 0x01, 0x02, where 0x35 is code 53 for "DHCP message type", 0x01 means one octet follows and 0x02 is the value of "offer".
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The following tables list the available DHCP options.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This table lists the DHCP message types.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] These codes are the value in the DHCP extension 53, shown in the table above.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] An option exists to identify the vendor and functionality of a DHCP client.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The information is a variable-length string of characters or octets which has a meaning specified by the vendor of the DHCP client.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] One method by which a DHCP client can communicate to the server that it is using a certain type of hardware or firmware is to set a value in its DHCP requests called the Vendor Class Identifier (VCI) (Option 60).
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The value to which this option is set gives the DHCP server a hint about any required extra information that this client needs in a DHCP response.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Some types of set-top boxes set the VCI to inform the DHCP server about the hardware type and functionality of the device.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] An Aruba campus wireless access point, for example, supplies value 'ArubaAP' as option 60 in its DHCPDISCOVER message.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP server can then augment its DHCPOFFER with an IP address of an Aruba wireless controller in option 43, so the access point knows where to register itself.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Setting a VCI by the client allows a DHCP server to differentiate between client machines and process the requests from them appropriately.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The relay agent information option (option 82) specifies container for attaching sub-options to DHCP requests transmitted between a DHCP relay and a DHCP server.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In small networks, where only one IP subnet is being managed, DHCP clients communicate directly with DHCP servers.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] However, DHCP servers can also provide IP addresses for multiple subnets.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In this case, a DHCP client that has not yet acquired an IP address cannot communicate directly with a DHCP server not on the same subnet, as the client's broadcast can only be received on its own subnet.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In order to allow DHCP clients on subnets not directly served by DHCP servers to communicate with DHCP servers, DHCP relay agents can be installed on these subnets.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A DHCP relay agent runs on a network device, capable of routing between the client's subnet and the subnet of the DHCP server.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP client broadcasts on the local link; the relay agent receives the broadcast and transmits it to one or more DHCP servers using unicast.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The IP addresses of the DHCP servers are manually configured in the relay agent.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The relay agent stores its own IP address, from the interface on which it has received the client's broadcast, in the *GIADDR* field of the DHCP packet.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP server uses the GIADDR-value to determine the subnet, and subsequently the corresponding address pool, from which to allocate an IP address.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When the DHCP server replies to the client, it sends the reply to the GIADDR-address, again using unicast.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The relay agent then retransmits the response on the local network, using unicast (in most cases) to the newly reserved IP address, in an Ethernet frame directed to the client's MAC address.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The client should accept the packet as its own, even when that IP address is not yet set on the interface.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Directly after processing the packet, the client sets the IP address on its interface and is ready for regular IP communication, directly thereafter.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If the client's implementation of the IP stack does not accept unicast packets when it has no IP address yet, the client may set the *broadcast* bit in the FLAGS field when sending a DHCPDISCOVER packet.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The relay agent will use the *255.255.255.255* broadcast IP address (and the clients MAC address) to inform the client of the server's DHCPOFFER.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The communication between the relay agent and the DHCP server typically uses both a source and destination UDP port of 67.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The client moves through DHCP states depending on how the server responds to the messages that the client sends.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The DHCP ensures reliability in several ways: periodic renewal, rebinding, and failover.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP clients are allocated leases that last for some period of time.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Clients begin to attempt to renew their leases once half the lease interval has expired.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] They do this by sending a unicast *DHCPREQUEST* message to the DHCP server that granted the original lease.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If that server is down or unreachable, it will fail to respond to the *DHCPREQUEST*.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] However, in that case the client repeats the *DHCPREQUEST* from time to time, so if the DHCP server comes back up or becomes reachable again, the DHCP client will succeed in contacting it and renew the lease.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If the DHCP server is unreachable for an extended period of time, the DHCP client will attempt to rebind, by broadcasting its *DHCPREQUEST* rather than unicasting it.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Because it is broadcast, the *DHCPREQUEST* message will reach all available DHCP servers.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If some other DHCP server is able to renew the lease, it will do so at this time.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] In order for rebinding to work, when the client successfully contacts a backup DHCP server, that server must have accurate information about the client's binding.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Maintaining accurate binding information between two servers is a complicated problem; if both servers are able to update the same lease database, there must be a mechanism to avoid conflicts between updates on the independent servers.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] A proposal for implementing fault-tolerant DHCP servers was submitted to the Internet Engineering Task Force, but never formalized.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] If rebinding fails, the lease will eventually expire.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] When the lease expires, the client must stop using the IP address granted to it in its lease.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] At that time it will restart the DHCP process from the beginning by broadcasting a `DHCPDISCOVER` message.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Since its lease has expired, it will accept any IP address offered to it.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Once it has a new IP address (presumably from a different DHCP server) it will once again be able to use the network.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] However, since its IP address has changed, any ongoing connections will be broken.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The basic methodology of DHCP was developed for networks based on Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4).
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Since the development and deployment of IPv6 networks, DHCP has also been used for assigning parameters in such networks, despite the inherent features of IPv6 for stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The IPv6 version of the protocol is designated as DHCPv6.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The base DHCP does not include any mechanism for authentication.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Because of this, it is vulnerable to a variety of attacks.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Because the client has no way to validate the identity of a DHCP server, unauthorized DHCP servers (commonly called "rogue DHCP") can be operated on networks, providing incorrect information to DHCP clients.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This can serve either as a denial-of-service attack, preventing the client from gaining access to network connectivity, or as a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Because the DHCP server provides the DHCP client with server IP addresses, such as the IP address of one or more DNS servers, an attacker can convince a DHCP client to do its DNS lookups through its own DNS server, and can therefore provide its own answers to DNS queries from the client.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This in turn allows the attacker to redirect network traffic through itself, allowing it to eavesdrop on connections between the client and network servers it contacts, or to simply replace those network servers with its own.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Because the DHCP server has no secure mechanism for authenticating the client, clients can gain unauthorized access to IP addresses by presenting credentials, such as client identifiers, that belong to other DHCP clients.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This also allows DHCP clients to exhaust the DHCP server's store of IP addresses—by presenting new credentials each time it asks for an address, the client can consume all the available IP addresses on a particular network link, preventing other DHCP clients from getting service.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] DHCP does provide some mechanisms for mitigating these problems.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] The Relay Agent Information Option protocol extension (usually referred to in the industry by its actual number as *Option 82*) allows network operators to attach tags to DHCP messages as these messages arrive on the network operator's trusted network.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] This tag is then used as an authorization token to control the client's access to network resources.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Because the client has no access to the network upstream of the relay agent, the lack of authentication does not prevent the DHCP server operator from relying on the authorization token.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Another extension, Authentication for DHCP Messages (RFC 3118), provides a mechanism for authenticating DHCP messages.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] As of 2002, this extension had not seen widespread adoption because of the problems of managing keys for large numbers of DHCP clients.
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] Architectural proposals from 2008 involve authenticating DHCP requests using 802.1X or PANA (both of which transport EAP).
[src:dhcp-snooping/dynamic-host-configuration-protocol] An IETF proposal was made for including EAP in DHCP itself, the so-called EAPoDHCP; this does not appear to have progressed beyond IETF draft level, the last of which dates to 2010.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] In computer networking, **IP address spoofing** or **IP spoofing** is the creation of Internet Protocol (IP) packets with a false source IP address, for the purpose of impersonating another computing system.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] The basic protocol for sending data over the Internet and many other computer networks is the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] The protocol specifies that each IP packet must have a header which contains (among other things) the IP address of the sender of the packet.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] The source IP address is normally the address that the packet was sent from, but the sender's address in the header can be altered, so that to the recipient it appears that the packet came from another source.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] The protocol requires the receiving computer to send back a response to the source IP address; therefore, spoofing is mainly used when the sender can anticipate the network response or does not care about the response.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] The source IP address provides only limited information about the sender.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] It may provide general information on the region, city and town from which the packet was sent.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] It does not provide information on the identity of the sender or the computer being used.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] IP address spoofing involving the use of a trusted IP address can be used by network intruders to overcome network security measures, such as authentication based on IP addresses.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] This type of attack is most effective where trust relationships exist between machines.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] For example, it is common on some corporate networks to have internal systems trust each other, so that users can log in without a username or password, provided they are connecting from another machine on the internal network, which would require them to be already logged in.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] By spoofing a connection from a trusted machine, an attacker on the same network may be able to access the target machine without authentication.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] IP address spoofing is most frequently used in denial-of-service attacks, where the objective is to flood the target with an overwhelming volume of traffic, and the attacker does not care about receiving responses to the attack packets.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Packets with spoofed IP addresses are more difficult to filter since each spoofed packet appears to come from a different address, and they hide the true source of the attack.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Denial-of-service attacks that use spoofing typically randomly choose addresses from the entire IP address space, though more sophisticated spoofing mechanisms might avoid non-routable addresses or unused portions of the IP address space.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] In DDoS attacks, the attacker may decide to spoof the IP source address to randomly generated addresses, so the victim machine cannot distinguish between the spoofed packets and legitimate packets.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] The replies would then be sent to random addresses that do not end up anywhere in particular.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Such packages-to-nowhere are called the backscatter, and there are network telescopes monitoring backscatter to measure the statistical intensity of DDoS attacks on the internet over time.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] IP address spoofing is a prerequisite for *reflection* attacks, in which the attacker sends requests with the victim's IP address as the spoofed source to third-party servers, which then send responses to the victim.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] When the response is substantially larger than the request, the technique is known as an *amplification* attack.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Protocols historically abused for amplification include DNS, NTP, SSDP, and memcached.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] The use of packets with a false source IP address is not always evidence of malicious intent.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] For example, in performance testing of websites, hundreds or even thousands of "vusers" (virtual users) may be created, each executing a test script against the website under test, in order to simulate what will happen when the system goes "live" and a large number of users log in simultaneously.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Since each user will normally have its own IP address, commercial testing products (such as HP LoadRunner, WebLOAD, and others) can use IP spoofing, allowing each user its own "return address" as well.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] IP spoofing is also used in some server-side load balancing.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] It lets the load balancer spray incoming traffic, but not need to be in the return path from the servers to the client.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] This saves a networking hop through switches and the load balancer as well as outbound message processing load on the load balancer.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Output usually has more packets and bytes, so the savings are significant.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Network services that authenticate clients solely by source IP address are inherently vulnerable to spoofing.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Historical examples include the Berkeley r-commands suite (rlogin, rsh, rcp), which are now largely deprecated in favour of SSH.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Some remote procedure call implementations and any application relying on IP-based access control lists without cryptographic authentication remain susceptible.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Packet filtering is one defense against IP spoofing attacks.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Ingress filtering, standardized as BCP 38 (RFC 2827), is performed at the gateway to a network and blocks incoming packets whose source address is inside the network.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] This prevents an outside attacker from spoofing the address of an internal machine.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Ideally, the gateway would also perform egress filtering on outgoing packets, which is the blocking of packets from inside the network with a source address that is not inside.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] This prevents an attacker within the network performing filtering from launching IP spoofing attacks against external machines.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] An intrusion detection system (IDS) is a common use of packet filtering, which has been used to secure the environments for sharing data over network and host-based IDS approaches.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] It is also recommended to design network protocols and services so that they do not rely on the source IP address for authentication.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] The CAIDA Spoofer project measures the prevalence of networks that fail to deploy source address validation by inviting volunteers to run a client that attempts to send spoofed packets from their network.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Some upper layer protocols have their own defense against IP spoofing attacks.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] For example, Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) uses sequence numbers negotiated with the remote machine to ensure that arriving packets are part of an established connection.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Since the attacker normally cannot see any reply packets, the sequence number must be guessed in order to hijack the connection.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] The poor implementation in many older operating systems and network devices, however, means that TCP sequence numbers can be predicted.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] The term ***spoofing*** is also sometimes used to refer to *header forgery*, the insertion of false or misleading information in e-mail or netnews headers.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] Falsified headers are used to mislead the recipient or network applications as to the origin of a message.
[src:dhcp-snooping/ip-address-spoofing] This is a common technique of spammers and sporgers, who wish to conceal the origin of their messages to avoid being tracked.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] In IEEE 802 LAN/MAN standards, the **medium access control** (**MAC**), also called **media access control**, is the layer that controls the hardware responsible for interaction with the wired (electrical or optical) or wireless transmission medium.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] The MAC sublayer and the logical link control (LLC) sublayer together make up the data link layer.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] The LLC provides flow control and multiplexing for the logical link (i.e.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] EtherType, 802.1Q VLAN tag etc), while the MAC provides flow control and multiplexing for the transmission medium.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] These two sublayers together correspond to layer 2 of the OSI model.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] For compatibility reasons, LLC is optional for implementations of IEEE 802.3 (the frames are then "raw"), but compulsory for implementations of other IEEE 802 physical layer standards.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] Within the hierarchy of the OSI model and IEEE 802 standards, the MAC sublayer provides a control abstraction of the physical layer such that the complexities of physical link control are invisible to the LLC and upper layers of the network stack.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] Thus, any LLC sublayer (and higher layers) may be used with any MAC.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] In turn, the medium access control block is formally connected to the PHY via a media-independent interface.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] Although the MAC block is today typically integrated with the PHY within the same device package, historically any MAC could be used with any PHY, independent of the transmission medium.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] For topologies with a collision domain (bus, ring, mesh, point-to-multipoint topologies), the channel access method controls when data is sent and when waiting is necessary to avoid collisions.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] Additionally, the MAC is also responsible for compensating for collisions by initiating retransmission if a jam signal is detected.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] When receiving data from the physical layer, the MAC block ensures data integrity by verifying the sender's frame check sequences and strips off the sender's preamble and padding before passing the data up to the higher layers.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] The local network addresses used in IEEE 802 networks and FDDI networks are called *MAC addresses*; they are based on the addressing scheme that was used in early Ethernet implementations.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] A MAC address is intended as a unique serial number.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] MAC addresses are typically assigned to network interface hardware at the time of manufacture.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] The most significant part of the address identifies the manufacturer, who assigns the remainder of the address, thus providing a potentially unique address.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] This makes it possible for frames to be delivered on a network link that interconnects hosts by some combination of repeaters, hubs, bridges and switches, but not by network layer routers.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] Examples of physical networks are Ethernet networks and Wi-Fi networks, both of which are IEEE 802 networks and use IEEE 802 48-bit MAC addresses.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] A MAC layer is not required in full-duplex point-to-point communication, but address fields are included in some point-to-point protocols for compatibility reasons.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] The channel access control mechanisms provided by the MAC layer are also known as a multiple access method.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] This makes it possible for several stations connected to the same physical medium to share it.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] Examples of shared physical media are bus networks, ring networks, hub networks, wireless networks and half-duplex point-to-point links.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] The multiple access method may detect or avoid data packet collisions if a packet mode contention based channel access method is used, or reserve resources to establish a logical channel if a circuit-switched or channelization-based channel access method is used.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] The channel access control mechanism relies on a physical layer multiplex scheme.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] The most widespread multiple access method is the contention-based CSMA/CD used in Ethernet networks.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] This mechanism is only utilized within a network collision domain, for example, an Ethernet bus network or a hub-based star topology network.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] An Ethernet network may be divided into several collision domains, interconnected by bridges and switches.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] A multiple access method is not required in a switched full-duplex network, such as today's switched Ethernet networks, but is often available in the equipment for compatibility reasons.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] Use of directional antennas and millimeter-wave communication in a wireless personal area network increases the probability of concurrent scheduling of non‐interfering transmissions in a localized area, which results in an immense increase in network throughput.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] However, the optimum scheduling of concurrent transmission is an NP-hard problem.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] Cellular networks, such as GSM, UMTS or LTE networks, also use a MAC layer.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] The MAC protocol in cellular networks is designed to maximize the utilization of the expensive licensed spectrum.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] The air interface of a cellular network is at layers 1 and 2 of the OSI model; at layer 2, it is divided into multiple protocol layers.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] In UMTS and LTE, those protocols are the Packet Data Convergence Protocol (PDCP), the Radio Link Control (RLC) protocol, and the MAC protocol.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] The base station has absolute control over the air interface and schedules the downlink access as well as the uplink access of all devices.
[src:dhcp-snooping/media-access-control] The MAC protocol is specified by 3GPP in TS 25.321 for UMTS, TS 36.321 for LTE and TS 38.321 for 5G.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] A **virtual local area network** (**VLAN**) is a local area network broadcast domain that is partitioned and isolated in a virtual network at the data link layer (OSI layer 2).
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] A VLAN behaves like a virtual network switch or network link that can share the same physical structure with other VLANs while staying logically separate from them.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLANs work by applying tags to network frames that are forwarded within the broadcast domain, creating the appearance and functionality of network traffic that behaves as if it were split between separate networks.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] In this way, VLANs can keep network applications separate despite being connected to the same physical network, and without requiring multiple sets of cabling and networking devices to be deployed.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLANs allow network administrators to group hosts together even if the hosts are not directly connected to the same network switch.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Because VLAN membership can be configured through software, this can greatly simplify network design and deployment.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Without VLANs, grouping hosts according to their resources requires relocating nodes or rewiring data links.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLANs allow devices that must be kept separate to share the cabling of a physical network and yet be prevented from directly interacting with one another.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] This managed sharing yields gains in simplicity, security, traffic control, and economy.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Many Internet hosting services use VLANs to separate customers' private zones from one another, enabling each customer's servers to be grouped within a single network segment regardless of where the individual servers are located in the data center.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Some precautions are needed to prevent traffic "escaping" from a given VLAN, an exploit known as VLAN hopping.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] To subdivide a network into VLANs, one configures network equipment.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Simpler equipment might partition only each physical port, in which case each VLAN runs over a dedicated network cable.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] More sophisticated devices can mark frames through VLAN tagging, so that a single interconnect (*trunk*) may be used to transport data for multiple VLANs.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Since VLANs share bandwidth, a VLAN trunk can use link aggregation, quality-of-service prioritization, or both to route data efficiently.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLANs address issues such as scalability, security, and network management.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Network architects set up VLANs to provide network segmentation.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Routers between VLANs filter broadcast traffic, enhance network security, perform address summarization, and mitigate network congestion.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] In a network utilizing broadcasts for service discovery, address assignment and resolution and other services, as the number of peers on a network grows, the frequency of broadcasts also increases.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLANs can help manage broadcast traffic by forming multiple broadcast domains.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Breaking up a large network into smaller independent segments reduces the amount of broadcast traffic each network device and network segment has to bear.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Switches may not bridge network traffic between VLANs, as doing so would violate the integrity of the VLAN broadcast domain.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLANs can also help create multiple layer 3 networks on a single physical infrastructure.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLANs are data link layer (OSI layer 2) constructs, analogous to Internet Protocol (IP) subnets, which are network layer (OSI layer 3) constructs.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] In an environment employing VLANs, a one-to-one relationship often exists between VLANs and IP subnets, although it is possible to have multiple subnets on one VLAN.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Without VLAN capability, users are assigned to networks based on geography and are limited by physical topologies and distances.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLANs can logically group networks to decouple the users' network location from their physical location.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] By using VLANs, one can control traffic patterns and react quickly to employee or equipment relocations.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLANs provide the flexibility to adapt to changes in network requirements and allow for simplified administration.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] A common infrastructure shared across VLAN trunks can provide a measure of security with great flexibility for a comparatively low cost.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Quality of service schemes can optimize traffic on trunk links for real-time (e.g.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] However, VLANs as a security solution should be implemented with great care as they can be defeated unless implemented carefully.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] In cloud computing VLANs, IP addresses, and MAC addresses in the cloud are resources that end users can manage.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] To help mitigate security issues, placing cloud-based virtual machines on VLANs may be preferable to placing them directly on the Internet.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] After successful experiments with voice over Ethernet from 1981 to 1984, W.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] David Sincoskie joined Bellcore and began addressing the problem of scaling up Ethernet networks.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] At 10 Mbit/s, Ethernet was faster than most alternatives at the time.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] However, Ethernet was a broadcast network and there was no good way of connecting multiple Ethernet networks together.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] This limited the total bandwidth of an Ethernet network to 10 Mbit/s and the maximum distance between nodes to a few hundred feet.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] By contrast, although the existing telephone network's speed for individual connections was limited to 56 kbit/s (less than one hundredth of Ethernet's speed), the total bandwidth of that network was estimated at 1 Tbit/s (100,000 times greater than Ethernet).
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Although it was possible to use IP routing to connect multiple Ethernet networks together, it was expensive and relatively slow.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Sincoskie started looking for alternatives that required less processing per packet.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] In the process, he independently reinvented transparent bridging, the technique used in modern Ethernet switches.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] However, using switches to connect multiple Ethernet networks in a fault-tolerant fashion requires redundant paths through that network, which in turn requires a spanning tree configuration.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] This ensures that there is only one *active* path from any source node to any destination on the network.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] This causes centrally located switches to become bottlenecks, limiting scalability as more networks are interconnected.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] To help alleviate this problem, Sincoskie invented VLANs by adding a tag (an individual label, such as A, B, C, and so on) to each Ethernet frame.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] In this scheme, each switch could be assigned to handle frames of a specific tag and ignore the rest.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] The networks could be interconnected with three spanning trees, one for each color.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] By sending a mix of different frame tags, the aggregate bandwidth could be improved.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Sincoskie referred to this as a *multitree bridge*.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] He and Chase Cotton created and refined the algorithms necessary to make the system feasible.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] This *color* is what is now known in the Ethernet frame as the IEEE 802.1Q header, or the VLAN tag.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] While VLANs are commonly used in modern Ethernet networks, they are not used in the manner first envisioned here.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] In 1998, Ethernet VLANs were described in the first edition of the IEEE 802.1Q-1998 standard.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] This was extended with IEEE 802.1ad to allow nested VLAN tags in service of provider bridging.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] This mechanism was improved with IEEE 802.1ah-2008.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Early network designers often segmented physical LANs with the aim of reducing the size of the Ethernet collision domain—thus improving performance.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] When Ethernet switches made this a non-issue (because each switch port is a collision domain), attention turned to reducing the size of the data link layer broadcast domain.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLANs were first employed to separate several broadcast domains across one physical medium.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] A VLAN can also serve to restrict access to network resources without regard to physical topology of the network.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLANs operate at the data link layer of the OSI model.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Administrators often configure a VLAN to map directly to an IP network, or subnet, which gives the appearance of involving the network layer.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Generally, VLANs within the same organization will be assigned different non-overlapping network address ranges.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] There is no issue with separate VLANs using identical overlapping address ranges (e.g. two VLANs each use the private network *192.168.0.0/16*).
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] However, it is not possible to route data between two networks with overlapping addresses without delicate IP remapping, so if the goal of VLANs is segmentation of a larger overall organizational network, non-overlapping addresses must be used in each separate VLAN.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] A basic switch that is not configured for VLANs has VLAN functionality disabled or permanently enabled with a *default VLAN* that contains all ports on the device as members.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] The default VLAN typically uses VLAN identifier 1.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Every device connected to one of its ports can send packets to any of the others.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Separating ports by VLAN groups separates their traffic very much like connecting each group using a distinct switch for each group.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Remote management of the switch requires that the administrative functions be associated with one or more of the configured VLANs.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] In the context of VLANs, the term *trunk* denotes a network link carrying multiple VLANs, which are identified by labels (or *tags*) inserted into their packets.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Such trunks must run between *tagged ports* of VLAN-aware devices, so they are often switch-to-switch or switch-to-router links rather than links to hosts.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] (Note that the term 'trunk' is also used for what Cisco calls "channels" : Link Aggregation or Port Trunking).
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] A router (Layer 3 device) serves as the backbone for network traffic going across different VLANs.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] It is only when the VLAN port group is to extend to another device that tagging is used.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Since communications between ports on two different switches travel via the uplink ports of each switch involved, every VLAN containing such ports must also contain the uplink port of each switch involved, and traffic through these ports must be tagged.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Switches typically have no built-in method to indicate VLAN to port associations to someone working in a wiring closet.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] It is necessary for a technician to either have administrative access to the device to view its configuration, or for VLAN port assignment charts or diagrams to be kept next to the switches in each wiring closet.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] The protocol most commonly used today to support VLANs is IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] The IEEE 802.1 working group defined this method of multiplexing VLANs in an effort to provide multivendor VLAN support.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Prior to the introduction of the 802.1Q standard, several proprietary protocols existed, such as Cisco Inter-Switch Link (ISL) and 3Com's Virtual LAN Trunk (VLT).
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Cisco also implemented VLANs over FDDI by carrying VLAN information in an IEEE 802.10 frame header, contrary to the purpose of the IEEE 802.10 standard.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Both ISL and IEEE 802.1Q perform *explicit tagging* – the frame itself is tagged with VLAN identifiers.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] ISL uses an external tagging process that does not modify the Ethernet frame, while 802.1Q uses a frame-internal field for tagging, and therefore does modify the basic Ethernet frame structure.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] This internal tagging allows IEEE 802.1Q to work on both access and trunk links using standard Ethernet hardware.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Under IEEE 802.1Q, the maximum number of VLANs on a given Ethernet network is 4,094 (4,096 values provided by the 12-bit VID field minus reserved values at each end of the range, 0 and 4,095).
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] This does not impose the same limit on the number of IP subnets in such a network since a single VLAN can contain multiple IP subnets.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] IEEE 802.1ad extends the number of VLANs supported by adding support for multiple, nested VLAN tags.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] IEEE 802.1aq (Shortest Path Bridging) expands the VLAN limit to 16 million.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Both improvements have been incorporated into the IEEE 802.1Q standard.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Inter-Switch Link (ISL) is a Cisco proprietary protocol used to interconnect switches and maintain VLAN information as traffic travels between switches on trunk links.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] ISL is provided as an alternative to IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] ISL is available only on some Cisco equipment and has been deprecated.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLAN Trunking Protocol (VTP) is a Cisco proprietary protocol that propagates the definition of VLANs on the whole local area network.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VTP is available on most of the Cisco Catalyst Family products.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] The comparable IEEE standard in use by other manufacturers is GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP) or the more recent Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP).
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol is an application of Multiple Registration Protocol that allows automatic configuration of VLAN information on network switches.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Specifically, it provides a method to dynamically share VLAN information and configure the needed VLANs.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLAN membership can be established either statically or dynamically.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Static VLANs are also referred to as port-based VLANs.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Static VLAN assignments are created by assigning ports to a VLAN.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] As a device enters the network, the device automatically assumes the VLAN of the port.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] If the user changes ports and needs access to the same VLAN, the network administrator must manually make a port-to-VLAN assignment for the new connection.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Dynamic VLANs are created using software or by protocol.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] With a VLAN Management Policy Server (VMPS), an administrator can assign switch ports to VLANs dynamically based on information such as the source MAC address of the device connected to the port or the username used to log onto that device.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] As a device enters the network, the switch queries a database for the VLAN membership of the port that device is connected to.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Protocol methods include Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP) and the somewhat obsolete GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP).
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] In a switch that supports protocol-based VLANs, traffic may be handled on the basis of its protocol.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] Essentially, this segregates or forwards traffic from a port depending on the particular protocol of that traffic; traffic of any other protocol is not forwarded on the port.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] This allows, for example, IP and IPX traffic to be automatically segregated by the network.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] VLAN cross connect (CC or VLAN-XC) is a mechanism used to create Switched VLANs, VLAN CC uses IEEE 802.1ad frames where the S Tag is used as a Label as in MPLS.
[src:dhcp-snooping/virtual-lan] IEEE approves the use of such a mechanism in part 6.11 of IEEE 802.1ad-2005.
